    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>When do galaxies settle into rotating disks? What does the progenitor of the Milky 
Way look like before the age of star formation?
Recent work has shown that massive ($10^{10-11} M_\odot$) star-forming galaxies 
are turbulent, rotating disks on the $M_*$-SFR relation out to $z\sim2-3$. 
While these most massive galaxies reveal interesting results, it remains unclear if 
the observed trends (turbulent disks, higher fraction of rotators with mass) hold true 
for the more typical, lower mass galaxies in the early Universe.

A banner science goal for the ALMA observatory is the blind detection and 
characterization of a Milky Way (MW) progenitor galaxy at z=3 within 24h.
We propose to observe three z=3 MW-analog galaxies, strongly lensed by the MACS1206 cluster, to 
detect the CO(3--2) line and characterize 
(a) their kinematics, 
(b) molecular gas content, and 
(c) total dust mass of these three MW-analogs.
</prp:abstract>
